..would be like saying a firehose might &quot;flood the ocean with water&quot;.. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.whitetoweronline.com"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.whitetoweronline.com/hall/icons/barth-sig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sovin>Sovin</A> at: 4/11/03 2:06:53 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 314<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/11/03 2:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=113>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Factoids</span><hr size=1> There are basicly three different forces you arte worrying about when dealing with the pusher, pressure from shock waves, ablation from the plasma, and radiation. The matterials used in spacecraft are fairly radiation resistant( space is a fairly radioactive environment), so the last is not much of an issue. Experiments were done while the project was being conducted to test the computer codes they were developing to model the effects of pressure and abaltion on the plate. Using high explosive driven plasma guns which projected plasma at preasures and speeds aproaching  that produced by a bomb. The velocity was less but the plasma density was greater. Later tests in the 1970's at LANL using electric driven plasma guns were able to more acuritly simulate bomb effects and concluded that the energy pulses would not cause ablation severe enough to degrade the performance of a nuclear pulse space vehicle, let alone immediately destroy it. Better simulations could be accomplished with current hydrodynamics models for bomb plasmas and supercomputes, but lacking either I can't test them myself.<br>
<br>
Radiation effects are more in my current area of knoledge. There are three basic ways to protect people from radiation: distance, shielding, and time. There is considerable shielding between the crew and the bomb. The first line is the channel filler and dense propellant in the pulse unit itself, which absorbes much of the initial radiation. The pusher also provides considerible shielding in and of itself, reduceing levels per shot of 10^5 rem at the face to 350 rem at the crew location without any other shielding. Of course the engine, propellant, structure, payload, and hydrogenous shielding around the crew during operation also comes into play, reducing total dose to the crew for a 1000-3000 pulse flight to 50 rem or less depending on the amout of crew shielding and flight time.<br>
<br>
To solve the time portion, the ship itself is made from low activation materials, meaning if activated by the radiation produced by the blast the nuclides produced have very short half-lives. Quoting from an ORION report to NASA, &quot;The nuclear-pulse-propulsion module has sufficiently low activation which permits manned access to most of the propulsion module minutes after shutdown. Manned access to the pusher itself is permitted within hours after shutdown.&quot; Thus the ship will be safe for the crew to travel in.<br>
<br>
On statistical cancer deaths from radiation, one must first realize how such estimates are developed before one can assess their value. The effect of low levels of radiation on the body is an area of intense debate in the scientific community, with experimental evidence ranging from it being harmful to benifical. The 'statistical fatal cancers' from low levels of radiation is produced by liniarly extrapolating high level data taken from survivors in Hiroshima and Nagasaki. Evidence suggests that this is clearly not the case, but government standards do not always change with scientific findings. The high natural cancer rate and random nature of radiation effects (one can be exposed to a single particle and get cancer, or be exposed to thousands and not) also makes effects hard to see. In reality probably no one would develope fatal cancer from the radiation of a launch due to diffusion over distance. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=q66stang>Q66stang</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/11/03 5:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=114>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Factoids</span><hr size=1> Nebobgrenville<br>
